[28:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thing in AI. Here they\'ve introduced something called continuous auto reggressive language models or COM for short. You see how large language models that you and I use today like chat GPT or Gemini or Grock or DeepSeek work is'

[29:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that they basically break down text into tokens. And how they generate the output is that they predict the next most probable word in your sequence one word at a time. This might sound crazy to'

[29:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you. Like you might think it\'s got to be way more complicated than that, right? Like how can we get Chad GBT to write a complete essay for you or write an entire professional research report for you. But actually behind the scenes'

[29:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s what it does. It just predicts the next most probable word one word at a time until it finishes your essay or research report or whatever you prompt it. You see, the problem with predicting one word at a time is that it\'s very'

[29:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'computationally inefficient, especially if your input or output is extremely long. The compute required basically increases pretty much exponentially as your sequence length increases. So, this traditional way of processing and'

[29:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'outputting text is not very efficient. Now instead of just breaking each word down into tokens and processing that sequence, what comm does is it basically converts this into a continuous vector. And if you compare COM with similarsized'

[30:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transformer models, you can see that it requires way fewer computations or basically flops than traditional language models while maintaining the same performance. Really quickly, here\'s the architecture behind it. So it first'

[30:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takes your input text and then it uses an autoenccoder to basically convert this into a continuous vector. The vector is then passed through this energybased generative head. And this model uses what they call an energy'

[30:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'score to basically evaluate the quality of its predictions and improve its performance. It\'s similar to like a loss function in a traditional transformer model. Anyways, after plugging it through this head and making the'

[30:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prediction, it\'s then passed through this decoder to basically convert the vector back into text that you and I can read. Now, the key here is that instead of predicting the next token or the next most probable word, it predicts entire'

[31:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vectors, which could be chunks of words. So, this drastically reduces the number of steps to generate text. And because the predictions are vectors, it also avoids some computational limitations from traditional transformers. The'

[31:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
